'''Scott Fraser McKenna''' (born 12 November 1996) is a Scottish professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Defender (association football)|centre-back]] for [[Croatian Football League|HNL]] club [[GNK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]] and the [[Scotland national football team|Scotland national team]].

==Club career==
===Aberdeen===
McKenna began his career in the [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] academy and was initially a [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|left back]] before moving to the centre. The [[Daily Record (Scotland)|''Daily Record'']] called him "one of the most promising defenders in the country".<ref name="Mcallion">{{Cite news |last=Mcallion |first=Kevin |date=22 March 2016 |title=Aberdeen tie down starlets Danny Rogers and Scott McKenna |work=Daily Record |publisher=Trinity Mirror |location=Glasgow |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/aberdeen-tie-down-starlets-danny-7609252#dW4b0sBp4vKTwAX5.97 |access-date=15 May 2016}}</ref>

McKenna made his professional debut for Aberdeen as a substitute against [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]] on 6 February 2016.<ref>{{Cite web |date=1 June 2016 |title=Young Dons' Debuts - Season 2015/16 |url=http://www.afc.co.uk/news/7945.php |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160604165015/http://www.afc.co.uk/news/7945.php |archive-date=4 June 2016 |access-date=2 July 2016 |website=www.afc.co.uk |publisher=Aberdeen F.C. }}</ref> His first start came against [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Heart of Midlothian]] on 16 May 2016.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Davie |first=Scott |date=12 May 2016 |title=Aberdeen 0–1 Heart of Midlothian |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36209713 |access-date=15 May 2016 |website=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=12 May 2016 |title=What Aberdeen 0–1 Hearts told us about each side's summer recruitment |work=The Scotsman |publisher=Johnston Press |location=Edinburgh |url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/competitions/premiership/what-aberdeen-0-1-hearts-told-us-about-each-side-s-summer-recruitment-1-4126915 |access-date=15 May 2016}}</ref> On 22 May 2016, he signed a new two-year contract with Aberdeen,<ref name="Mcallion" /> In November 2016, McKenna moved on loan to [[Scottish Championship]] side [[Ayr United F.C.|Ayr United]] for 28 days, his second time on loan with the club.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Wilson |first=Mike |date=11 November 2016 |title=Ayr United sign Aberdeen defender Scott McKenna on loan |work=Daily Record |publisher=Trinity Mirror |location=Glasgow |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/ayr-united-sign-aberdeen-defender-9238439 |access-date=13 November 2016}}</ref> His loan was subsequently extended until the end of the season.<ref>{{Cite web |date=20 January 2017 |title=McKenna extends stay at Ayr |url=https://www.afc.co.uk/2017/01/20/mckenna-extends-stay-at-ayr/ |access-date=4 January 2021 |website=www.afc.co.uk |publisher=Aberdeen F.C.}}</ref>

In October 2017, McKenna extended his Aberdeen contract until 2021. The club rejected a bid from [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] to buy him in January 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |date=14 January 2018 |title=Aberdeen turn down Hull City's offer for Scott McKenna |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42681484 |access-date=14 January 2018 |website=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC}}</ref> In January 2018, McKenna scored from more than 35 yards in Aberdeen's 3–1 win against [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]]. He claimed in an interview after the match that Kilmarnock skipper [[Kris Boyd]] urged him to "shoot" so he obliged.<ref>{{Cite web |date=27 January 2018 |title=Scott McKenna-Kilmarnock Reaction |url=https://redtv.afc.co.uk/tv/video/vod/2799 |access-date=29 January 2018 |website=redtv.afc.co.uk |publisher=Aberdeen F.C.}}</ref> On 7 March 2018, McKenna signed a new contract extension until 2023.<ref>{{Cite web |date=7 March 2018 |title=Aberdeen: Scott McKenna extends Pittodrie contract 'to kick on' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43322133 |access-date=7 March 2018 |website=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC}}</ref>

Aberdeen rejected an offer of £3.5 million for McKenna from [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] in August 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |last=McLaughlin |first=Chris |date=22 August 2018 |title=Scott McKenna: Aberdeen reject Celtic bid of around £3.5m |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45271654 |access-date=22 August 2018 |website=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC}}</ref> Later in August, Aberdeen rejected a larger offer from [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=McLauchlin |first=Brian |date=31 August 2018 |title=Scott McKenna: Aberdeen turn down Aston Villa bid for defender |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45373501 |access-date=31 August 2018 |website=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC}}</ref> During the summer 2019 transfer window, Aberdeen rejected offers from [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] and [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] for McKenna after he handed in a transfer request.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Sutherland |first=Jonathan |date=5 August 2019 |title=Aberdeen: Scott McKenna hands in transfer request |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49238176 |access-date=5 August 2019 |website=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC}}</ref>

In December 2019 Aberdeen chairman Dave Cormack confirmed the club had received no offers or approaches from other clubs for McKenna or teammate [[Sam Cosgrove]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Couse |first=Stephen |date=16 December 2019 |title=Aberdeen: No offers for Sam Cosgrove & Scott McKenna, says chairman |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50816798 |access-date=4 January 2021 |website=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC}}</ref> McKenna suffered a torn hamstring during a Scottish Cup tie at [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]] on 29 February 2020.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Smith |first=Tyrone |date=3 March 2020 |title=Scott McKenna: Aberdeen and Scotland defender likely to miss rest of season |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51726076 |access-date=3 March 2020 |website=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC}}</ref>

In August 2020 he was one of eight Aberdeen players who received a suspended three-match ban from the [[Scottish FA]] after they breached restrictions relating to the [[COVID-19 pandemic in Scotland|COVID-19 pandemic]] by visiting a bar earlier in the month.<ref>{{Cite web |date=28 August 2020 |title=Celtic's Boli Bolingoli gets three-game ban; 'Aberdeen eight' receive three-match suspended ban |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/53951005 |access-date=4 January 2021 |website=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC}}</ref> Aberdeen entered transfer negotiations with Nottingham Forest regarding McKenna in September 2020, which meant that he was left out of the Aberdeen team for a match with [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=21 September 2020 |title=Scott McKenna: Nottingham Forest poised to sign Aberdeen defender |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54226184 |access-date=21 September 2020 |website=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC}}</ref>

===Nottingham Forest===
On 23 September 2020, McKenna moved to [[EFL Championship]] side [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] for an undisclosed fee,<ref>{{Cite web |date=23 September 2020 |title=McKenna moves to The Reds |url=https://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/news/2020/september/nottingham-forest-complete-signing-of-scott-mckenna-from-aberdeen/ |access-date=4 January 2021 |website=www.nottinghamforest.co.uk |publisher=Nottingham Forest F.C.}}</ref> confirmed by Aberdeen as a "club-record" amount<ref>{{Cite web |date=23 September 2020 |title=Scott McKenna departs the Dons |url=https://www.afc.co.uk/2020/09/23/scott-mckenna-departs-the-dons/ |access-date=4 January 2021 |website=www.afc.co.uk |publisher=Aberdeen F.C.}}</ref> reported to be £3 million that could rise to £6 million.<ref>{{Cite web |date=23 September 2020 |title=Scott McKenna: Nottingham Forest sign Aberdeen and Scotland defender |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54266405 |access-date=4 January 2021 |website=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC}}</ref> He made his Forest debut on 25 September 2020 in a 1–0 defeat to [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=25 September 2020 |title=Huddersfield beat Forest for first win |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54200433 |access-date=4 January 2021 |website=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC }}</ref> He scored his first goal for the club in a 2–1 win over [[Coventry City]] on 4 November 2020.<ref>{{Cite web |date=4 November 2020 |title=Nottingham Forest 2-1 Coventry |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54714755 |access-date=5 November 2020 |website=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC}}</ref> He was voted as [[List of Nottingham Forest F.C. records and statistics#Player of the Season|Forest's Player of the Season]] for the [[2021–22 Nottingham Forest F.C. season|2021–22]] campaign,<ref>{{Cite web |last=Club |first=Nottingham Forest Football |title=McKenna wins UK Meds Player of the Season |url=https://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/news/2022/june/13/mckenna-wins-uk-meds-player-of-the-season/ |access-date=2022-06-15 |website=Nottingham Forest Football Club |date=13 June 2022 }}</ref> during which they won promotion to the [[Premier League]].<ref name = collarbone/> McKenna missed significant parts of the [[2022–23 Nottingham Forest F.C. season|2022–23]] season due to hamstring and collarbone injuries.<ref name = collarbone>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/65378895 |title=Nottingham Forest: Scott McKenna to miss remainder of Premier League season |website=BBC Sport |date=24 April 2023 |accessdate=25 April 2023}}</ref>

On 30 January 2024, McKenna joined [[Danish Superliga]] club [[F.C. Copenhagen|Copenhagen]] on loan for the remainder of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/news/2024/january/30/mckenna-loaned-to-copenhagen/|title=McKenna loaned to Copenhagen|website=www.nottinghamforest.co.uk|date=30 January 2024|accessdate=30 January 2024}}</ref> On 5 June 2024, Forest announced he would be leaving in the summer when his contract expired.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Club |first=Nottingham Forest Football |date=2024-06-05 |title=Forest confirm retained list |url=https://www.nottinghamforest.co.uk/news/2024/june/05/forest-confirm-retained-list/ |access-date=2024-06-06 |website=Nottingham Forest Football Club}}</ref>

===Las Palmas===
On 8 August 2024, McKenna joined [[UD Las Palmas|Las Palmas]] on a three-year contract.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.udlaspalmas.es/en/news/scott-mckenna-nuevo-jugador-de-la-ud-las-palmas |title=Scott McKenna joins UD Las Palmas |website=UD Las Palmas |date=8 August 2024 |accessdate=8 August 2024}}</ref>

===Dinamo Zagreb===
In 2025 McKenna joined Dinamo Zagreb in Croatia, winning a league and cup double in his first season

==International career==
McKenna captained the [[Scotland national under-19 football team|Scotland under-19s]] in a 2–2 draw with the [[Czech Republic national under-19 football team|Czech Republic]] in 2014.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2 September 2014 |title=Scott McKenna captains the Scotland U19s |url=http://www.afc.co.uk/news/4943.php |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150530115842/http://www.afc.co.uk/news/4943.php |archive-date=30 May 2015 |access-date=15 May 2016 |website=afc.co.uk |publisher=Aberdeen F.C.}}</ref> McKenna made his first appearance for the [[Scotland national under-21 football team|Scotland under-21s]] in September 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |date=24 September 2017 |title=Motherwell 0-1 Aberdeen: Scott McKenna praised for big part in win |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41378142 |access-date=24 September 2017 |website=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC}}</ref>

McKenna was selected for the [[Scotland national football team|full national squad]] in March 2018,<ref>{{Cite web |date=12 March 2018 |title=Six new faces in Alex McLeish's Scotland squad for March friendlies |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43369364 |access-date=12 March 2018 |website=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC}}</ref> and made his full international debut in a 1–0 defeat against [[Costa Rica national football team|Costa Rica]] on 23 March.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Dowden |first=Martin |date=23 March 2018 |title=Scotland 0–1 Costa Rica |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43380252 |access-date=23 March 2018 |website=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC}}</ref> In his fourth game for Scotland, a 1–0 defeat to [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] on 2 June 2018, McKenna was made team [[captain (association football)|captain]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Lamont |first=Alasdair |date=3 June 2018 |title=Mexico 1–0 Scotland: Captaincy caps fairytale season - Scott McKenna |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44347310 |access-date=3 June 2018 |website=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC}}</ref> On 11 October 2018, McKenna came on a second-half substitute in a 2–1 defeat against [[Israel national football team|Israel]], marking his competitive debut for Scotland.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Lamont |first=Alasdair |date=11 October 2018 |title=Israel 2-1 Scotland: Ten-man Scotland embarrassed by Israel |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45741590 |access-date=14 October 2018 |website=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC}}</ref>

On 7 June 2024, McKenna was named in Scotland's squad for the [[UEFA Euro 2024]] finals in Germany.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/record-breaking-goalkeeper-gordon-out-scotland-euro-2024-squad-2024-06-07/|title=Record-breaking goalkeeper Gordon out of Scotland's Euro 2024 squad|date=7 June 2024|access-date=15 June 2024|website=Reuters}}</ref> He appeared in all three of the team's matches at the tournament, coming on as a substitute against both [[Germany national football team|Germany]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c844x4y3ee3t|title=Ruthless Germany humble 10-man Scotland in Euro 2024 opener|website=BBC Sport|access-date=15 June 2024}}</ref> and [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]], before starting against [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]] as Scotland finished bottom of [[UEFA Euro 2024 Group A|Group A]] with one point from three matches.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/news/028e-1b2c127c5b92-e020507872a2-1000--scotland-1-1-switzerland-clarke-s-men-keep-group-a-hopes-/|title=Scotland 1-1 Switzerland: Clarke's men keep Group A hopes alive|access-date=24 June 2024|website=UEFA}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/match/2036186--scotland-vs-hungary/lineups/|title=Scotland vs Hungary: Line-ups|access-date=24 June 2024|website=UEFA}}</ref>

==Personal life==
A pupil at [[Webster's High School]] in [[Kirriemuir]],<ref>[https://www.tes.com/magazine/archived/scotland-players-old-schools-send-good-luck-messages Scotland players' old schools send good luck messages], Henry Hepburn, [[TES (magazine)]], 11 June 2021</ref> McKenna supported Celtic as a boy.<ref name = scotsman/> He is distantly related to the late [[Alan Gilzean]], who was a cousin of McKenna's maternal grandmother.<ref name="scotsman">{{Cite news |last=Pattullo |first=Alan |date=15 February 2020 |title=Interview: Aberdeen's Scott McKenna on his sudden rise to the Scotland captaincy, why he wants to leave Pittodrie and why Aston Villa's move for him fell through |work=The Scotsman |publisher=JPIMedia |location=Edinburgh |url=https://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/interview-aberdeen-s-scott-mckenna-on-his-sudden-rise-to-the-scotland-captaincy-why-he-wants-to-leave-pittodrie-and-why-aston-villa-s-move-for-him-fell-through-1-5091147 |access-date=17 February 2020}}</ref> His father Ian played semi-professionally in the [[Scottish Football League]] for [[Forfar Athletic F.C.|Forfar Athletic]] and [[Montrose F.C.|Montrose]] in the 1990s.<ref name = scotsman/><ref>then went on to become a director of McKenna group services [http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/player6/ianmckenna.html Ian McKenna], Post War English & Scottish Football League A - Z Players Transfer Database</ref>

